<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,944,1224]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Note: Name originally stated as masculine, but here considered neuter, because it is based on the Greek noun “spelaion” (cave), following 
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN &amp; International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature" box="[503,645,1053,1079]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" refId="ref101125" refString="ICZN (International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature) (1999) International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth edition. London. International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature. Available from: http: // www. iczn. org / iczn / index. jsp (accessed 24 September 2019)" type="url" year="1999">ICZN (1999</bibRefCitation>
: Art. 30.1.2). Actually, although Salgado declared the genus as masculine gender, he correctly used neuter gender for the 
<typeStatus box="[804,852,1089,1115]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">type</typeStatus>
species name.
</paragraph>
